replies.body:
Skill floor and skill ceiling (also called skilled cap) are a measure of the skill/reward.

Having a low skill floor means you don't need to be very good at the champion/game to do well. Having a high skill floor means you need to have a good understanding of the champion, its mechanics, and how they work within the game to even be passably effective.

Low skill floor: {{champion:86}} 
High skill floor: {{champion:143}} 

Skill ceiling, or skill cap, is a measure of potential. How dangerous is a champion in the hands of an extremely skilled player? This is rather subjective, as even very simple champions can be extremely versatile and powerful in the right hands. Generally, this is reserved for champions that have nuances to their design that can be leveraged to maximize performance that are difficult to master. {{champion:92}} often is toted as a high skill ceiling champion due to the damage output potential from animation canceling. {{champion:64}} is another common champion that can do amazing things when you get really good with him. Low skill ceiling implies the champion is easy to achieve a high level of play.

Sometimes, you have champs that I would say have both a low floor and a high ceiling. My classic example would be {{champion:11}} . He is super easy to be good with, but when in the hands of someone who plays him hardcore he does unbelievable things.
